The new Civil Code is being prepared for six companies out of ten
The impending effectiveness of the new Civil Code and the Commercial Corporations Act as of 1 January 2014 has been intensively prepared by six firms out of ten.
Only eight percent of the company representatives surveyed said they had not addressed the issues related to the two key codes in their company at all.
This is according to a survey by the law firm Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal, which surveyed the views of 108 Czech companies.
In the context of the upcoming effective date for the two key codes, it is only now at the last minute that a number of managers are beginning to realise the significant effect on their companies' business.
The biggest changes in private law in the last 50 years will, in our opinion, affect all citizens and companies in the Czech Republic.
Because of the lavishing of politicians, the business sector has long been in the dark about whether revolutionary changes will eventually take place or not.
"Now, however, they only have a few weeks left to make the transition to the new right for their companies without any complications," said the partner of Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal, Jan Spáčil.
Of the 61 percent of companies intensively involved in the new codes, 26 percent said their firms had already taken all the necessary measures to be prepared in time.
Furthermore, 35 per cent of companies of this number are about to take the necessary measures in the near future.
Against this, one in five companies has not yet dealt with recoding, yet it has a concrete idea of how to prepare for them.
A total of 11 percent have no opinion and are unable to assess the issue.
Only eight per cent of companies admit that the issues associated with the recodes have not yet been addressed.
The most important legal issue related to the new Civil Code is the contracting of new contracts (21 per cent) for the largest number of companies surveyed, followed by a solution to the terms of trade (16 per cent) and changes in the Land Register and in liability for damages (after 10 percent).
Contracts will take place one of the most important novelties of the entire recodification, namely the unification of contract modifications only within the framework of the new Civil Code.
The current parallel regulation in both the Civil and Commercialodes will cease to be extinguished, with the result that the contract law should become more transparent for citizens and entrepreneurs alike.
"In the case of entrepreneurs, the new regulation will offer many innovations with an emphasis on greater freedom of arrangement of relationships," said Lukas Poddaný, attorney at Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal.
In the context of the Business Corporations Act, almost a quarter of companies consider the issue of increasing the liability of the statutory bodies to be the most important topic.
This is followed by topics on changes to the convening and conduct of the general meeting (15 per cent) and representing the company (14 per cent).
The new legislation means tightening up the obligations and possible impacts for the statutory bodies, especially in a situation where a company is at risk of bankruptcy or reaches it.
"In practice, this means that if the members of the boards of directors and the managers of the companies do not act with the care of a proper treasurer and do not avert the impending bankruptcy of the company, they may lose the benefit of the acquired for the performance of the post for the last two years," Spáčil said.
