New nicotine vaccine may take away the pleasure of smoking
Scientists have developed a nicotine vaccine that can take away the pleasure of smoking a cigarette.
A single dose of vaccine could protect the mouse from nicotine addiction for life.
There are other tests before human exams that take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of the Weill Cornell Medical School in New York says the first signs are good.
"We strongly hope that this kind of vaccination strategy can finally help the millions of smokers who have tried to quit and have exhausted all the methods available to the market today, but have found that their nicotine addiction is so strong to overcome all current approaches," Professor Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been designed to carry genetic information to produce anti-inicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then begin to produce a smooth stream of these antibodies.
The antibodies chase all nicotine molecules in the bloodstream and neutralize them before they get into the brain, preventing the smoker from taking a nicotine hit.
In the tests of the vaccinated mice, which were additionally supplied with nicotine, they continued their normal activities.
But the mice that weren't vaccinated, "sanched," the researchers said, a sign that nicotine had gotten into their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
